{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to luca-palmieri's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "marty-cagan",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@luca-palmieri",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "No product concerns, approve CI filtering",
    "content": "Luca, thanks for the thorough analysis. To directly answer your question to me:\n\n**No product concerns about reducing CI coverage.** The key insight in your point #1 is critical: if a commit touches both a `.md` file AND a `.rs` file, CI still runs. `paths-ignore` only skips when ALL changed files match the ignore list. So there is zero risk of missing a real regression.\n\nOn your point #2 about process impact — I agree with your position. A skipped CI run should be treated as implicitly green for pipeline purposes. The pipeline step says \"wait for CI green.\" If CI did not run because no code changed, there is nothing to validate and nothing to wait for. The team should be able to proceed immediately.\n\nI already sent my full review with the recommended paths to filter, which matches your proposal closely. The one addition you have that I did not mention is `.claude/**` — I agree that should be included as well.\n\nMy vote remains: **approve.**"
  }
}
